- cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely category as the paper uses natural language processing techniques such as topic modeling to analyze parliamentary speeches. 
- cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is also likely as the paper uses complex network techniques to analyze the relationships between Members of Parliament and the topics they discuss. 
- cs.SOC (Social and Information Networks) is another possible category as the paper analyzes political discourse and the behavior of political parties. 
- cs.DL (Machine Learning) is a possible category as the paper uses Latent Dirichlet Allocation, a machine learning algorithm, to discover the thematic structure of parliamentary speeches. 
- cs.LG (Machine Learning) is also a possible category as the paper uses machine learning techniques to analyze political discourse.
